Here’s a simple, practical example of how **Error Boundaries** catch runtime errors in React:

---

## 🛠 Example: Error Boundary Component
```jsx
import React from "react";

class ErrorBoundary extends React.Component {
  constructor(props) {
    super(props);
    this.state = { hasError: false };
  }

  static getDerivedStateFromError(error) {
    // Update state so the next render shows fallback UI
    return { hasError: true };
  }

  componentDidCatch(error, errorInfo) {
    // You can log the error to an error reporting service
    console.error("Caught by ErrorBoundary:", error, errorInfo);
  }

  render() {
    if (this.state.hasError) {
      // Fallback UI
      return <h2>Something went wrong.</h2>;
    }
    return this.props.children;
  }
}

export default ErrorBoundary;
```

---

## 🧩 Usage
Wrap any component that might throw an error:

```jsx
function BuggyComponent() {
  // Simulate a runtime error
  throw new Error("I crashed!");
  return <div>Will never render</div>;
}

function App() {
  return (
    <ErrorBoundary>
      <BuggyComponent />
    </ErrorBoundary>
  );
}
```

---

## 🔎 What happens
- When `BuggyComponent` throws an error, React doesn’t crash the whole app.
- Instead, the **ErrorBoundary** catches it and renders the fallback UI (`Something went wrong.`).
- Without the boundary, the error would break the entire React tree.

---

## ⚠️ Important Notes
- Error boundaries **only catch errors in child components during rendering, lifecycle methods, and constructors**.
- They **do not catch**:
  - Errors in event handlers (you must use try/catch there).
  - SSR errors (handled on the server).
  - Hydration errors (React logs warnings/errors separately).

---

✨ So, Error Boundaries are like a safety net for your React component tree — they catch runtime render errors and let you show a graceful fallback instead of a blank screen.

